"@type\": \"Answer\",\n        \"text\": \"Many light bars — particularly mini bars and magnetic-mount options — are designed for DIY installation. Full-size bars with permanent mounts, wiring integration, and controllers are more complex and often benefit from professional installation.\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"@type\": \"Question\",\n      \"name\": \"What light bar colors are legal on my truck?\",\n      \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n        \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n        \"text\": \"This depends entirely on your state and whether your vehicle is authorized for emergency use. Amber is typically the safest color for general warning purposes. Red, blue, green, and white flashing lights are restricted in many states to authorized emergency vehicles. Always verify your local regulations.\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"@type\": \"Question\",\n      \"name\": \"How much should I expect to spend on a quality truck light bar?\",\n      \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n        \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n        \"text\": \"Entry-level mini bars from reputable brands start around a few hundred dollars. Full-size professional lightbars with traffic advisors and integrated controls can range from $2,000 to $5,000 or more depending on configuration.\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n</script>"
